stimulus:
Welcome to the experiment!



Consent to Participate

You are being asked to participate in a psychology experiment.

Risks: The main risk is that you might get bored while completing the task.

Benefits: There are no direct benefits, but your participation will help us learn about how people judge visual images.

By pressing any key, you agree to participate in this study voluntarily.

If you do not wish to participate, you may close this browser window now.

Press any key to begin.

This study examines how people make simple judgments.

During the first task, you will see pairs of pictures appear one after the other.

The first picture will be a real-life image and the second picture will be an abstract painting.

The first image is simply a warning signal for the abstract painting and should be ignored.

Your task is to judge how visually pleasant each abstract painting is.

Put your index fingers on the E and I keys of your keyboard.

If the abstract painting is less visually pleasant than average, please press the E key on the left.

If the abstract painting is more visually pleasant than average, please press the I key on the right.

Note that the first (real-life) image can sometimes bias judgments of the abstract paintings.

Please try your absolute best not to let the real-life images bias your judgment of the abstract paintings.

After each trial we will ask you whether your judgment of the abstract painting was influenced by the real-life image.

If your judgment of the abstract painting was influenced by the image that came before it, then press the 1 key.

If your judgment of the abstract painting was NOT influenced by the image that came before it, then press the 0 key.

Here are some examples of the types of pictures that you will see during the task:

Real-life images
Abstract paintings

Press thespace bar to continue.

We will now provide you with an opportunity to practice the task. Remember: You should judge whether each abstract

painting is more or less visually pleasant than average by pressing the E or the I key. And if you think your

rating of the abstract paintingwas influenced by the real-life image that appeared just before it, press the 1 key.

And if it was not influenced by the real-life image, press the 0 key. When you are ready to try a few practice

responses, hit the space bar.

Ready? Press the space bar to begin.

Good! The test phase will now begin. Keep going as before.

As a reminder: If the abstract painting is less visually pleasant than average, press the E key. And if it is more visually pleasant than average, press the I key.

During the second and final task, you will see how a past participant in a study just like this one responded to the abstract paintings.

Just like you, this participant saw two pictures back to back: first a real-life image and then an abstract painting.

Just like you, this participant was told that the first image is simply a warning signal for the abstract painting and should be ignored.

The participant’s task, just like yours, was to judge how visually pleasant each abstract painting is.

If the abstract painting was less visually pleasant than average, the participant pressed the E key on the left.

If the abstract painting was more visually pleasant than average, the participant pressed the I key on the right.

The participant was warned that the first (real-life) image could sometimes bias judgments of the abstract paintings.

Therefore, the participant was asked to try their absolute best not to let the real-life images bias their judgment of the abstract paintings.

On each trial, we will show you the real-life image and the abstract painting that the previous participant saw.

Afterwards, we will tell you whether the participant rated the abstract painting as Pleasant or as Unpleasant

Similar to the previous task, your job will be to tell us whether you think the other participant’s judgment of the abstract painting was influenced by the real-life image.

If you think that the participant’s judgment of the abstract painting was influenced by the image that came before it, then press the 1 key.

And if you think that the participant’s judgment of the abstract painting was NOTinfluenced by the image that came before it, then press the 0 key.

Remember: On each trial, we will show you the real-life image and the abstract painting that a previous participant saw. Afterwards, you will be shown if they rated the abstract painting as pleasant or as unpleasant.

If you think that the participant’s rating of the abstract painting was influenced by the real-life image that appeared just before it, press the 1 key. And if you think it was notinfluenced by the real-life image, press the 0 key.
